\cs17\super $}{ Story Files}}#{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super #}{ story}}}{\b\f1 The Story Files
\par }{\f1 
\par The Magnetic Scrolls games as originally distributed were in a somewhat complex data format, different for most platforms, without a clear distinction between the interpreter code and the data for the game. The interpreter uses its own story file format, 
identified by the file name extension ".mag".
\par 
\par Currently, story files can only be created by extracting the data from C64 disk images (i.e. files representing the contents of the games released for the Commodore 64). These files are identified by having a f
ile name ending with ".d64". Disk images for "The Pawn", "The Guild of Thieves", "Corruption", "Jinxter" and "Fish" can be found on the Internet at the }{\f1\ul Arnold}{\v\f1 arnold}{\f1  C64 archive.
\par 
\par To convert these files to the interpreter's own format, the }{\b\f1 Xtract64}{\f1  program, which is included with this interpreter, must be used.}{\b\f1  Xtract64}{\f1  is a Win32 console program, so must be run from an MS-DOS prompt. Run }{\b\f1 
Xtract64}{\f1  without any arguments to read a help screen. The syntax is:
\par }\pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\adjustright \f2\fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 
\par }{\f6 \tab Xtract64 disk1.d64 disk2.d64 story.mag
\par }{\f1 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 For example, for "The Pawn", the command line might be:
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f6 \tab Xtract64 pawn1.d64 pawn2.d64 pawn.mag
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 
\par The story files can also be downloaded from Stefan Meier's }{\f1\ul Magnetic Scrolls Memorial}{\v\f1 meier}{\f1 .}{\page }{\f1 
\par }{\cs17\b\f1\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super K}{ Graphics files}}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super $}{ Graphics Files}}#{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super #}{ graphics}}}{\b\f1 The Graphics Files
\par }\pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 
The Magnetic Scrolls adventures were as well known for the quality of their graphics as of their text. The interpreter supports a single graphics file format (".gfx"), which is based on the graphics files released with the original Amiga version of the ga
mes. The graphics files used by Magnetic can be obtained from the Internet, from either }{\f1\ul Paul David Doherty's}{\v\f1 doherty}{\f1  web page or Stefan Meier's }{\f1\ul Magnetic Scrolls Memorial}{\v\f1 meier}{\f1 .
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\adjustright \f2\fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 Included with the interpreter is }{\b\f1 GfxLink}{\f1 , a tool to build graphics files from the Amiga releases of the Magnetic Scrolls games. }{\b\f1 GfxLink}{\f1 
 is a Win32 console program, so must be run from an MS-DOS prompt. To use }{\b\f1 GfxLink}{\f1 , supply as arguments the directory containing the Amiga files and the output graphics file name, e.g.
\par 
\par }\pard \s15\fi720\widctlpar\adjustright {GfxLink C:\\UAE\\Games\\ThePawn Pawn.gfx
\par }\pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 
\par \page 
\par }{\cs17\b\f1\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super #}{ titles}}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super $}{ Title Screens}}K{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super K}{ Title screens}}}{\b\f1 Title Screens}{\f1 
\par 
\par Magnetic also supports title pictures and music, the files for which can be obtained from the }{\f1\ul Magnetic Scrolls Memorial}{\v\f1 meier}{\f1  web page. The title 
files should have the same name as the game file, except that the picture files must end in \ldblquote .png\rdblquote  and the music files in \ldblquote .mp3\rdblquote . The titles appear whenever a new game is loaded into Magnetic.
\par \page 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\b\f1\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super K}{ Original documentation}}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright 
\fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super $}{ Original Documentation}}#{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super #}{ documentation}}}{\b\f1 Documentation from the Original Packages
\par }{\f1 
\par To prevent software pirates from spreading their programs, Magnetic Scrolls added a password protection to most of their games. However, }{\f1\uldb Xtract64}{\v\f1 story}{\f1 
 will offer to remove this type of protection. Despite this, most games still cannot b
e won without the original documentation, since it often contains vital clues. There are currently two web sites that offer a growing amount of scanned material from the original packages: Stefan Meier's }{\f1\ul Magnetic Scrolls Memorial}{\v\f1 meier}{
\f1 ; and }{\f1\ul The Magnetic Scrolls Gallery}{\v\f1 boerner}{\f1  by Rochus Boerner, which also features scanned material and many screen shots.
\par 
\par \page 
\par }{\cs17\b\f1\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super K}{ Using the interpreter}}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super $}{ Using the Interpreter}}#{\footnote 
\pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super #}{ interpreter}}}{\b\f1 Using the Interpreter
\par }{\f1 
\par As you are reading this file you probably have the Magnetic interpreter already. Its most recent release can always be found at the }{\f1\ul Interactive Fiction Archive}{\v\f1 archive}{\f1 .
\par }\pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 Magnetic supports input line editing and history to make typing more convenient. All the common editing keys work as you would expect. Cursor up and curs
or down step up and down through the input history, respectively. Text can be pasted into the input line using the standard paste keys (i.e. }{\b\f1 Ctrl+v}{\f1  or }{\b\f1 Shift+Insert}{\f1 ).
\par }\pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 This Windows port of the Magnetic Interpreter behaves as you would expect of a Windows pr
ogram: to operate use either the menus or the toolbar. The behaviour of each menu item is given below, along with the equivalent toolbar symbol.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\keepn\widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f1\fs20\lang2057\cgrid {File Menu
\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-2268\li2268\keepn\widctlpar\tx-2410\tx2268\outlinelevel0\adjustright \f1\fs20\lang2057\cgrid {
\par \{bmc open.bmp\}Open New Game\tab Opens a file open dialog to choose a new game to be loaded. Any game currently in memory will be lost if a new game is selected. The names of the four most recently loaded games are shown just above the }{\b Exit}{
 item in this menu and can be selected directly. A new game can be loaded at any time.
\par 
\par \tab When loading the game file (e.g. }{\b Pawn.mag}{), the interpreter will also try to load a }{\uldb graphics file}{\v graphics}{ of the same name but with the extension ".gfx" (i.e. }{\b Pawn.gfx}{
 in this example). If this graphics file is found then the pictures are displayed in a separate window.
\par 
\par \{bmc script.bmp\}Script\tab Opens a file save dialog to select a file to save the script of the current game to. The script contains all text output by the game and commands input by the user. Select this item again to turn scripting off.
\par 
\par \{bmc record.bmp\}Record\tab Opens a file save dialog to select a file to save command input to. This file will contain the text of all commands input by the user. Select this item again to turn recording off.
\par 
\par \{bmc play.bmp\}Playback\tab Opens a file open dialog to select a command input file, which will usually have been produced using the Record menu item. The game will play back all the commands in the file as if the user had typed them in.
\par 
\par Exit\tab Exits the interpreter.
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\f1 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\keepn\widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f1\fs20\lang2057\cgrid {View Menu
