\pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super #}{ internal}}}{\b\f1 Magnetic Internal Data Format
\par }{\f1 
\par Unless otherwise stated all words are big-endian. The datafile format is as follows:
\par 
\par }{\f6 1) Game file (.mag)
\par 
\par Offset Size Explanation
\par -----------------------
\par    0    4   Magic word 'MaSc'
\par    4    4   Size of datafile
\par    8    4   Size of header (42 in this version)
\par   12    2   Game version:
\par               0. Pawn
\par               1. Guild of Thieves
\par               2. Jinxter
\par               3. Myth, Corruption, Fish!
\par               4. Magnetic Windows versions
\par   14    4   Size of code [1]
\par   18    4   Size of string data ( <=65536 ) [2]
\par   22    4   Size of string data part 2 (the rest) [3]
\par   26    4   Size of dictionary [4]
\par   30    4   String table offset ( <=[2]+[3] )
\par }\pard \s15\fi-1474\li1474\widctlpar\adjustright {\f6   34    4   Offset in the code block up to which undo and restart data is saved. This originally had a very clear meaning as the C64 versions used read-only swapping from disk after that offs
et. Other versions are somewhat less obvious, but looking at the save-routines should help.
\par   38    4   Undo offset, ie. the offset in the code block at which data for the undo operation is saved, usually in the beginning of the main loop. A zero value works just nicely if you don't care about undo (which isn't foolproof anyway).
\par }\pard \s15\widctlpar\adjustright {\f6   42   [1]  Code data
\par   ++   [2]  String data 1
\par   ++   [3]  String data 2
\par   ++   [4]  Dictionary data
\par 
\par 2) Graphics file (.gfx). This is basically just an encapsulation of the original Amiga graphics files.
\par 
\par Offset Size Explanation
\par -----------------------
\par    0    4   Magic word 'MaPi'
\par    4    4   Size of datafile
\par  8+4*k  4   Offset to the k:th picture data
\par }{\f1 
\par The format of the individual pictures is somewhat obscure, but the details can be found in the routine ms_extract() in the source file emu.c.
\par }{
